segments.text: The innovation program, they had a thing called the TIG, Technology Innovation Group, and
the thrust of this was to try to develop new technologies, and as it turned out, this focused
largely on computer technology.
And we had, I don't know how many cities we eventually worked with.
I think it was something between 50 and 60 cities in the state of Texas.
In addition to that, we had, through the NSF program, we became the backup agency to
help Little Rock, Arkansas, and it was a tremendously successful program.
And then in the, what, about 76, I guess it was, then we hired Don Moore, who replaced
me as the director of the center.
Of course, it went on up until...
The early 80s, the federal funding report disappeared, things went downhill pretty rapidly.
It was a separate center at that time, and I had nothing to do with it.
I had to dry it up, and NSF supported dry it.
And I guess, to me, one of the saddest elements of that whole thing was that the cities, I
guess I shouldn't have been too surprised at that, but I was.
We had, over the decade, in the 70s...
It was the last half of it, and we had developed, I thought, excellent rapport with the cities.
You know, they're very applied in their concerns, and you have to be careful about the words
that you use in working with them.
For example, we learned rather quickly, you don't say research, because when you say research,
a city councilman in Abilene or whatever will conjure up some guy in a white coat surrounded
by testicles.
And they're not always going to find one.
So we called it property solving.
But in spite of that, and in spite of the fact that we had done, I thought, a hell of
a lot of good things for the cities, Don Moore, and I was never a more able guy, would draw
any support from the Texas cities to continue that.

in the wrong view, frankly, but because this still is a land grant.
I went to college.

be a good idea to do it again.
